Lithified, dark greenish gray wackestone with glauconite and sand size grains. Abundant disseminated pyrite, sand size. Abundant small benthic foraminifers. Macros: common bivalve fragments 1 cm, bryozoan, urchin spine.

Lithified, dark gray packstone with glauconite and abundant disseminated pyrite. Coarse sand size grains. Benthic foraminifers abundant. Macros: bivalve fragments (1 cm), common, occasional bryozan, an urchin spine.

Lithified dark greenish gray grainstone with coarse sand size grains. The grains are composed of abundant glauconite, pyrite, reddish brown grains and carbonate. Macrofossils include benthic foraminifers, bivalves, Cycloclypeus, bryozoan, full colonies,

Lithified, light brown grainstone with moderate biotubation and sand size grains. Burrows (mm scale) are infilled with brown material (gypsum or dolomite?). Larger burrows (few cm scale) are dark gray or dark brown. Macrofossils include: benthic forams, molds of bivalves and urchin spine. Sparse kartic cavities.
to pal

Lihtified, light brow until 72 cm where there is a sharp contact, below this is is light gray, skeletal grainstone with sand size grains and up to granule size shells and fragments. Shells have been replaced most commonly with gypsum and to a lesser extent anhydrite. In some shells both gypsum and anhydrite co-exist. Burrows (mm scale) have been infilled with brown material likely gypsum, Also present, large burrows (several cm's long) and dark gray in color. Glauconite grains are common. Macrofossils: bivalves, gastropods and bryozoan up to 2 cm long. One bivalve is 5 cm long. A sand dollar replaced by gypsum is 3 cm long. Corals (Acropora, Fungiid). There are large and small benthic forams. Sharp contact at 72 cm

Lithified, dark brown grainstone with sand size grains and abundant shell material. Below 104 cm it is light brown grainstone. Abundant glauconite grains. Burrows (mm scale) infilled with gypsum. Larger (up to a few cm long) shells have been replaced by gypsum and to a lesser extent anhydrite. In some shells both gypsum and anhydrite coexist. Macros include bivalves and gastropods up to 3 cm long. Bryozoan up to 5 mm, urchin spines sand size, and snakk and large benthic forams (Cycloclypeus) . Color variability dark brown up to 104 cm an light brown below could be a function of diagenesis (more gypsum in the Section above 104 cm)

Lithified, dolomitic grainstone with sand size grains and patches of darker brown (mottling). Possibly due to uneven diagenesis. Sparse and fine sand size glauconite grains. Shells are less abundant than in prior Sections. There are some solution cavities but most have been filled by gypsum. Shell fragments (mainly of bivalves) have been replaced by gypsum. Bivalves, gastropods. Bryozoan in upper 18 cm. Some urchin spines. Small and large benthic forams including Cycloclypeus, sand dollar. One anhydrite nodule.

Lithified, litght brown dolomitic grainstone with sand size grains and patches of darker brown (mottling). Possibly due to uneven diagenesis. Sparse and fine sand size glauconite grains. Shells are less abundant than in prior Sections. There are some solution cavities but most have been filled by gypsum. Shell fragments (mainly of bivalves) are sand size and not easy to identify. Bivalves, urchin spines, bryozoan colony. Small benthic forams
to pal

Lithified, litght brown dolomitic grainstone with sand size grains and patches of darker brown (mottling). Possibly due to uneven diagenesis. Sparse and fine sand size glauconite grains. Shells are less abundant than in prior Sections. There are some solution cavities but most have been filled by gypsum. Shell fragments (mainly of bivalves) are sand size and not easy to identify. Bivalves, urchin spines, bryozoan colony. Small benthic forams

Lithified, brown dolomitic mudstone with complete bioturbation. Burrows abundant and some filled with coarser sand size grains (possibly pyrite and glauconite). Small (mm-scale) burrows filled with gypsum. Some burrows also contain anhydrite nodules (few mm long). Shells are sparse but when present they have been replaced by gypsum. In a few gypsum is being replaced by anhydrite. A 3 mc long bivalve and <1cm bivalve fragments abundant. Occasional gastropod and bryozoan colony (< 1 cm) and small benthic forams.

Lithified, light brown dolomitic mudstone with complete bioturbation. Burrows abundant and some filled with coarser sand size grains (possibly pyrite and glauconite). Small (mm-scale) burrows filled with gypsum. Some burrows also contain anhydrite nodules (few mm long). Shells are sparse but when present they have been replaced by gypsum. In a few gypsum is being replaced by anhydrite. Bivalve fragments < 2 cm most are smaller, couple of urchin spines a large coral polyp, gastropod and forams

Lithified, brown dolomitic mudstone with complete bioturbation. Burrows abundant and some filled with coarser sand size grains (possibly pyrite and glauconite). Small (mm-scale) burrows filled with gypsum. Some burrows also contain anhydrite nodules (few mm long). Shells are sparse but when present they have been replaced by gypsum. In a few gypsum is being replaced by anhydrite. Foraminifers common

LIthified, skeletal packstone with sand size grains and abundant macrofossils. Anhydrite nodules (mm to cm scale) are common. Both anhydrite and gypsum replacement of shells also common. Grains include pyrite and/or glauconite. Bivalves abundant, corals abundant fragments Acropora and Funjiid, gastropods, occsional bryozoan and forams

Lithified, creamy brown dolomitic packstone with fine sand size grains and abundant solution carities. Burrows at mm scale present and infilled with gypsum. Acropora fragments (>3 cm) and other unidentified pieces of corals, bivalve and gastropod fragments some benthic forams. Less anhydrite than in the Section above

LIthified, light brown to dark brown dolomitic wackestone with sand size grains and large (10 cm long and 5 wide) anhydrite crystals with chicken wire structure. Burrows abundant the small ones (mm scale) are filled with gypsum. Smaller anhydrite nodules (1-2 cm) also common. Macros upper 18 cm include bivalves and coral fragments and occasional foram. Within the large anhydrite crystals there are Porites corals. In the lower 10 cm there are bivalve fragments replaced by gypsum
to pal
Lithified, light brown dolomitic packstone with sand size grains and complete bioturbation. Macros include small bivalve fragments, benthic forams and a sand dollar fragment.

Lithified, brown, dolomitic wackestone with fine sand size grains and complete bioturbation. Burrows infilled with coarser material exhibit solution cavities. Shell replacement is mainly by gypsum and anhydrite nodules are not as common. Macrofossils are small bivalve fragments and bryozoan and forams
Partially lithified but extensively compressed dolomitic mudstone with shades of white cream, creamy green, gray, brown and gray. Looks like a clay rich mudstone
